Negative-interest-rate club
Brussels—For most of the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in containing the powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Fed has kept interest rates at zero and has also undertaken several unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchases.
The BoE, the BOJ, and the ECB have all followed the Fed’s lead, implementing their own versions of what is known as “quantitative easing” (QE).
But inflation has failed to gain a reasonable boost anywhere.
Despite these countries' efforts to combat deflationary pressures, their monetary policies—and economic performance—are diverging.
The US and UK growth is now strong enough to allow for the exit of expansionary policies and rate hikes, while the eurozone and Japan are intensifying their QE programs, pushing long-term policy rates further into negative territory.
What accounts for this difference?
A brief answer is debt.
For decades, the US and UK have had current account deficits, making them debtor nations, while the eurozone and Japan have maintained external surpluses, positioning them as creditor nations.
Negative interest rates benefit debtor nations but harm creditor nations, hence the introduced negative interest rates post-global economic crisis stimulated the recovery of the US and the UK, but had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, most creditor nations – countries with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland – have been experiencing negative interest rates, not just for long-term government bonds and other “risk-free” debts, but also for medium-term bonds.
This is not good.
Despite the limited effectiveness of low interest rates, these economies' central banks still adhere to this policy.
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot benefit the economy, they will deflect,反驳 the notion that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — on the surface, this seems unassailable.
Actually, this argument is full of holes.
Basic economics courses also mention the curious phenomenon of the backward-bending supply curve of savings: at certain points, lower interest rates lead to higher savings.
Because lower interest rates reduce income for savers, they will cut spending, especially if they have saved for retirement.
All of this does not negate the general rule — which forms the basis of modern monetary policy — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other expenditures.
Only the effects differ due to the different debt conditions of the economies.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, so the debtor should benefit regardless of what the creditors lose due to extremely low interest rates.
But in an economy with large net foreign asset positions, creditors naturally outnumber debtors.
For a country with substantial foreign debt, the situation is the opposite.
Therefore, the effectiveness of interest rate floor monetary policy differs between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important because foreign asset positions were typically small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
But now, foreign asset positions of the major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, partly due to the leverage that led to the global financial crisis of 2007-2008.
In fact, at the national level, leverage is still increasing.
Although current account imbalances have eased somewhat since the financial crisis began, they have not reversed.
This means surplus countries are further strengthening their creditor positions, widening the divide with deficit economies.
Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have large current account surpluses when oil prices are high, making them notable exceptions to the divergence in foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, world oil prices have plummeted, reversing these countries' wealth trends.
Their export revenues have plummeted—many countries saw a halving—and forced them into deficits, relying on vast sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodities boom.
Now, substantial cuts in spending are inevitable.
Industrialized economies face entirely different challenges.
Their problem, to some extent a luxury one, is ensuring that consumers spend the windfall gains from falling import prices.
However, in creditor countries, negative interest rates do not seem to be advancing this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This division also exists within the eurozone.
Although the eurozone as a whole is a creditor economy, it includes debtor countries.
Debtor economies such as Spain and Portugal now have persistent current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
But traditional debtor countries' current account surpluses are too high, leading to an ongoing asymmetry between debtor and creditor countries.
The most noteworthy development is that Germany's current account surplus has risen to nearly 8% of GDP since the financial crisis, meaning that its accumulated surplus during this period exceeds the historical total.
According to the current trend, Germany's foreign asset position could increase from 60% of GDP to 100%.
Central bank governors should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend toward central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem less patient, fretting over low inflation despite the gradual closure of output gaps, and full employment achieved in the US and Japan.
Debtor country central bank governors must stop using more monetary easing that may be detrimental to production.
Instead, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is slow, and wait for the base effect from the decline in oil prices to fade.
ECB governor Draghi recently admitted that current monetary policy approaches may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more easy fixes is not the solution.
